In the forums I read that there are doubts that the fuel transfer system based on a micro G acceleration works well. I guess the engineers know what it does.

But, without being able to avoid it, I had an idea. What if instead of micro acceleration the tanker-tank set is rotated? There is an old way of transforming a rotary movement into a longitudinal one: the Archimedean screw. The tanker should have such a screw built in, a metallic helical plane.

It would rotate the tank assembly with the RCS in the appropriate direction. For example, if the helicoid extends toward the [outlet valve] in a clockwise direction, the rotation should be counterclockwise. The fuel will go against the walls (tangential compression) and the outlet valve should be on the periphery of the tank (therefore the outlet end of the tank should be concave and not convex).

Do you think this would work?

I have seen the Falcon Heavy launch around April 2019 from the ground of the Air Force Station in front of the small spaceX launch/landing control center. It was amazing and so impressive to see the brightness of the rocket exhaust. Like a sharp, well defined slice of the sun thats propelling the rocket upwards. Incredible! (This is where I can really see the benefit of HDR/high brightness LCDs in the future :D )

The sound of the rocket was equally impresive and thats where my following question comes from. You can hear it in the Videos as well - the loud, sometimes a bit metallic sounding "crackling" sound of the rocket. Almost like popping small firework in a tin can sumerged in shallow water over and over again multiple times per second. What are the physics behind this sound phenomenom - the unmistakeable "plopping and crackling" noise only heard during large rocket launches? I have found out that it is almost none existent in small rockets and gets more pronounced, the larger the rocket gets. Please share the most nerdy, scientific and in depth explanation which is existent on earth with me. :D
